The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
		 Tuesday, June 22, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	Krishnagar, June 21: Naren Mandol, a trader, was arrested for threatening to kill a schoolteacher after he turned down his request to upgrade his daughters marks. 				 																																	Police said Nirjhar Mandol, 40, of Hanskhali High School, about 65 km from Calcutta, had been receiving threat calls from Naren, his neighbour. Nadia superintendent Benoy Chakraborty said a time bomb minus a detonator was found from the courtyard of the teachers house this morning. 				 																																	Calcutta: The government will soon start plying luxury buses to Jharkhand. Initially, they will go to Jamshedpur, Ranchi, Nowadi, Bokaro, Dumka, Dhanbad, Jharia, Ghatsila, Giridih and Deoghar. The luxury coaches will conform to Bharat Stage II norms and travel daily. They will operate from the city, Barasat, Barrackpore, Haldia, Durgapur, Asansol and Burdwan. 				 																																	Calcutta: The lawyers ceasework on June 23 suffered a setback today with Left-dominated Democratic Lawyers Association opting out. But unfazed members of the Bar Council said they are firm on going ahead with it.
